Armed Basque separatist group ETA announces cease-The armed Basque separatist group ETA has announced an open-ended cease-fire, a newspaper reported late Wednesday. 
ETA, whose name stands for Basque Homeland Freedom, has killed nearly 800 people since 1968 in its campaign for Basque independence. 
A former leader of the Basque separatist group ETA urged the government Thursday to transfer ETA prisoners to jails inside the Basque country as a first step towards peace talks. 
Since then, the government has been under pressure from both hardline and moderate Basque nationalists, and even the mainstream Socialist opposition party, to make a significant gesture to ETA on its long-standing demand that separatist prisoners be transferred to the Basque country, or at least closer to it. 
A bomb damaged a discotheque in Spain's northern Basque region Sunday in an attack claimed by Basque separatists. 
Spain said Friday it will move 21 Basque separatist inmates from far-flung prisons to jails closer to their home region, a move seen as a gesture to the armed Basque group ETA. 
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar said that the week-long unilateral cease-fire started today by the militant Basque separatist group Eta is a propaganda stunt. 
Police and politicians have blamed ETA. 
